\title{An Absence of Judgment: On AI's Fundamental Limitations in Research}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
Large language models are fundamentally incapable of judgment, despite their ability to mimic the language of judgment. This distinction necessitates examining not only their linguistic output but also the concrete actions and outcomes that their words produce. However, this lack merely prevents us from treating them as true agents, \textit{not} as extracting mundane utility from them as tools. This paper is an investigation into the creation of a research-grade dataset using OpenAI's Deep Research in February 2025, acting as a case study --- and our ``autoethnographic'' reflection upon the use of this tool for what Zvi Moshowitz calls ``mundane utility."

Here, we will also give our understanding of the necessary prerequisites for an ``agentic'' tool, and why we believe that this infrastructure, at this time, does not satisfy that criteria. We will also discuss the fundamental lack of judgment that these models exhibit, and why it is this core incapability which prevents an accumulation of patterns-shaped-like-knowledge to answer Dwarkesh's question to Cohen: ``what do you make of the fact that these things have basically the entire corpus of human knowledge memorized and they haven't been able to make a single new connection that has led to a discovery? Whereas if even a moderately intelligent person had this much stuff memorized, they would notice — Oh, this thing causes this symptom.'' We assert that the lack of induction exhibited by even currently accessible frontier models like o3-mini-high, answers this question.

\section{Agentic Systems Framework}

\subsection{Goal-Related Characteristics}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Goal Following vs Goal Setting
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Agentic systems are goal-following systems
            \item This contrasts with AGI, which can set its own goals
            \item Key distinction: Agentic systems require external input for goals
        \end{itemize}
    \item Core Components
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Goal processing capabilities
            \item Execution mechanisms
            \item Assessment and reporting functions
        \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section{Deep Research Analysis}

\subsection{Observed Limitations}
Our investigation reveals fundamental limitations in Deep Research's capabilities, particularly in its ability to engage in genuine research activities. These limitations manifest in several key areas:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Failure in guideline adherence
    \item Surface-level competence without true comprehension
    \item Inability to question assumptions
    \item Lack of systematic approach
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Uncanny Valley of Research}
We observe what we term the "uncanny valley of research" - where the system produces outputs that superficially resemble research work but lack crucial elements of genuine research capability:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Always produces output without questioning assumptions
    \item Takes initial search results as "gospel"
    \item Lacks self-correction or revision processes
    \item Absence of winnowing or filtering process
\end{itemize}

\section{System Design Requirements}

\subsection{Context Management}
Effective research tools require sophisticated context management capabilities:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Transparent context window visibility
    \item Token management strategies
    \item Source tracking and documentation
    \item Ability to "forget" or remove irrelevant content
    \item Tombstones for discarded thoughts
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Research Process Support}
The research process must be supported through structured mechanisms:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Structured todo lists for research steps
    \item Clear documentation of considered sources
    \item Management of working context windows
    \item Integration points for human judgment
    \item Outline-driven context switching
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Stage-Based Approach}
Research development requires distinct stages, each with specific requirements:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Literature finding
    \item Literature extraction
    \item Outline building
    \item First draft creation
    \item Revision process
    \item Editing and output
    \item Documentation requirements for each stage
\end{itemize}

\section{Human-AI Collaboration Framework}

\subsection{Judgment Integration}
The integration of human judgment is crucial given AI's fundamental limitations:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Recognition of AI judgment deficiency
    \item Strategic points for human intervention
    \item Validation and verification processes
    \item Beyond simple confirmation mechanisms
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Tool-Centric Approach}
AI systems must be treated as tools rather than agents:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Leveraging AI capabilities appropriately
    \item Managing limitations and boundaries
    \item Integration with human research processes
\end{itemize}

\section{Future Development}

\subsection{Technical Requirements}
Future development must address several key technical areas:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Improved context management
    \item Better token efficiency
    \item Enhanced source tracking
    \item Robust documentation systems
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Process Requirements}
Process improvements are needed in several areas:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Non-waterfall approach to research
    \item Flexible stage management
    \item Improved human-AI interaction patterns
    \item Documentation standards
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
Our investigation demonstrates that while current AI systems show promise in supporting research activities, they fundamentally lack the capability for true judgment and systematic research. The path forward lies in developing better tools that acknowledge these limitations while providing structured support for human-AI collaboration in research contexts.

\end{document}
